ta }"></span> is the probability of making a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors#Type_II_error" title=3D"Type I and typ=
e II errors">type&nbsp;II error</a> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/False_negative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"False negative">false n=
egative</a>) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_probabili=
ty" title=3D"Conditional probability">conditional</a> on there being a true=
 effect or association.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Background">Background</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(statistic=
s)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Background"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_test" tit=
le=3D"Statistical hypothesis test">Statistical hypothesis test</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_test" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Statistical test">Statistical testing</a> uses data from =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Sa=
mpling (statistics)">samples</a> to assess, or make <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_inference" title=3D"Statistical inference">in=
ferences</a> about, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_=
population" title=3D"Statistical population">statistical population</a>. Fo=
r example, we may measure the yields of samples of two varieties of a crop,=
 and use a two sample test to assess whether the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mean_values" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean values">mea=
n values</a> of this yield differs between varieties.
</p><p>Under a frequentist hypothesis testing framework, this is done by ca=
lculating a test statistic (such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/T-statistic" title=3D"T-statistic">t-statistic</a>) for the dataset, wh=
ich has a known theoretical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probab=
ility_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribu=
tion</a> if there is no difference (the so called null hypothesis). If the =
actual value calculated on the sample is sufficiently unlikely to arise und=
er the null hypothesis, we say we identified a statistically significant ef=
fect.
</p><p>The threshold for significance can be set small to ensure there is l=
ittle chance of falsely detecting a non-existent effect. However, failing t=
o identify a significant effect does not imply there was none. If we insist=
 on being careful to avoid false positives, we may create false negatives i=
nstead. It may simply be too much to expect that we will be able to find sa=
tisfactorily strong evidence of a very subtle difference even if it exists.=
 Statistical power is an attempt to quantify this issue.
</p><p>In the case of the comparison of the two crop varieties, it enables =
us to answer questions like:
</p>
<ul><li>Is there a big danger of two very different varieties producing sam=
ples that just happen to look indistinguishable by pure chance?</li>
<li>How much effort do we need to put into this comparison to avoid that da=
nger?</li>
<li>How different do these varieties need to be before we can expect to not=
ice a difference?</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Description">Description</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(statist=
ics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Description"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_error=
s" title=3D"Type I and type II errors">Type I and type II errors</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PowerOfTest.png" class=3D"mw-file-description=
"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Pow=
erOfTest.png/250px-PowerOfTest.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"264" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"734" data-file-height=
=3D"774"></a><figcaption>Illustration of the power of a statistical test, f=
or a two sided test, through the probability distribution of the test stati=
stic under the null and alternative hypothesis. <i>=CE=B1</i> is shown as t=
he <span style=3D"color:blue">blue area</span>, the probability of rejectio=
n under null, while the <span style=3D"color:red">red area</span> shows pow=
er, 1 =E2=88=92 <i>=CE=B2</i>, the probability of correctly rejecting under=
 the alternative.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Suppose we are conducting a hypothesis test. We define two hypotheses <s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmln=
