<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Power_in_different_discipli=
nes">Power in different disciplines</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(statistics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
11" title=3D"Edit section: Power in different disciplines"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Several studies have attempted to estimate typical levels of statistical=
 power across different academic fields. One common approach uses meta-anal=
yses to assess whether individual studies have sufficient power to detect t=
he average effect size estimated from the meta-analysis itself. This method=
 essentially asks: how likely is each study to detect the consensus effect =
found in the broader literature? These assessments consistently find low le=
vels of statistical power across many disciplines.  For example, using this=
 method median power is 18% in economics,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(statistics)#cite_=
note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> 10% in political science,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(statistics)#=
cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> 36% in psychology,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(statistics)#=
cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> and 15% in ecology and evolutionary biology.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Power_(statistics)#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extension">Extension</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(statistics)=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Extension"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bayesian_power">Bayesian po=
wer</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(s=
tatistics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Bayes=
ian power"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequentist" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Frequentist">frequentist</a> setting, parameters are as=
sumed to have a specific value which is unlikely to be true. This issue can=
 be addressed by assuming the parameter has a distribution. The resulting p=
ower is sometimes referred to as Bayesian power which is commonly used in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clinical_trial" title=3D"Clinical t=
rial">clinical trial</a> design.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Predictive_probability_of_s=
uccess">Predictive probability of success</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPower_(statistics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Predictive probability of success"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequentist" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Frequentist">frequentist</a> power and Bayesian power use=
 statistical significance as the success criterion. However, statistical si=
gnificance is often not enough to define success. To address this issue, th=
e power concept can be extended to the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Predictive_probability_of_success" title=3D"Predictive prob=
ability of success">predictive probability of success</a> (PPOS). The succe=
ss criterion for PPOS is not restricted to statistical significance and is =
commonly used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clinical_trial" t=
itle=3D"Clinical trial">clinical trial</a> designs.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Software_for_power_and_samp=
